# Typst Writing Conventions

## Project Layout

Split the project into clear concerns. Never put template logic and prose in the same file.

```
main.typ              # Entry point: imports template, includes sections
template/
  conf.typ            # Page setup, fonts, show rules, title page layout
sections/
  01-introduction.typ # One file per top-level section (= heading)
  02-methodology.typ
  ...
context/              # Reference material for the AI — never compiled
  brief.md            # Project brief, goals, audience
  outline.md          # Detailed outline / plan
  source-notes.md     # Raw notes, extracts, summaries
assets/               # Images, CSV, bib files used by the document
```

- `main.typ` should be short: apply the template with `#show`, set metadata, then `#include` each section in order.
- Each section file is plain prose starting with a level-1 heading (`=`). It must not set page/font/show rules.
- The `template/` folder owns all formatting. Content files never import it directly.
- The `context/` folder holds auxiliary material (briefs, outlines, notes, summaries) in Markdown. These files are **not** included in the Typst build — they exist solely as reference for the AI when drafting or revising prose. Always read relevant `context/` files before writing a section.

## Naming

- Section files are prefixed with a two-digit number for ordering: `01-`, `02-`, etc.
- Use lowercase kebab-case for all `.typ` filenames.
- Labels use kebab-case: `<sec-introduction>`, `<fig-results-table>`.

## Writing Style

- One sentence per line in source (semantic line breaks). This produces cleaner diffs and makes reordering easy.
- Keep lines under ~100 characters when practical.
- Separate paragraphs with a blank line.
- Use `//` comments sparingly in prose files — only for TODO or editorial notes.

## Typst Idioms

- Prefer `set` / `show` rules in the template over inline styling in prose.
- Use `#figure` with a `caption` for every table, image, or code listing.
- Give every figure a `<label>` and reference it with `@label` in the text.
- Use `@label` cross-references instead of hard-coded section numbers.
- Keep raw data (CSV, images, bib) in a top-level `assets/` directory.

## When Adding a New Section

1. Create `sections/NN-section-name.typ` with the next available number prefix.
2. Add a corresponding `#include "sections/NN-section-name.typ"` line in `main.typ`.
3. The section file starts with `= Section Title` — nothing else before it.
